  <h1>
    Forms
  </h1>
  <p>
    Form elements are extremely common and often very similar, so by default,
    the styles are based on the elements themselves and don't require additional
    classes.
  </p>

  <h2>
    Inputs & Labels
  </h2>
  <p>
    Apart from checkboxes, radio buttons, and range inputs, all input types
    should have the same basic styles. It's recommended to wrap each
    <code>label</code> and <code>input</code> pair in a <code>div</code> to
    preserve the vertical rhythm of the page.
  </p>
  <p>
    Best practices apply here. Make sure each <code>input</code> has an
    <code>id</code> attribute that matches the <code>for</code> attribute of its
    <code>label</code>. The <code>input</code> also must have a valid
    <code>type</code>, and most likely a <code>name</code>.
  </p>

  <div>
    <label for="basic-input">Basic Input</label>
    <input id="basic-input" type="text" name="basic-input">
  </div>

<pre>
&lt;div&gt;
  &lt;label for="basic-input"&gt;Basic Input&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;input id="basic-input" type="text" name="basic-input"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</pre>

  <h2>
    Textareas
  </h2>
  <p>
    The <code>textarea</code> element is meant for longer-form text, so it is
    allowed to be wider than the default <code>input</code>. Do not set the
    <code>cols</code> attribute, as the width should be determined by the size
    of the screen. You may use <code>rows</code> to set the initial height,
    though, and users will be able to resize it as they see fit.
  </p>

  <div>
    <label for="basic-textarea">Basic Textarea</label>
    <textarea id="basic-textarea" name="basic-textarea" rows="5"></textarea>
  </div>

<pre>
&lt;div&gt;
  &lt;label for="basic-textarea"&gt;Basic Textarea&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;textarea id="basic-textarea" name="basic-textarea" rows="5"&gt;&lt;/textarea&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</pre>

  <h2>
    Buttons
  </h2>
  <p>
    The <code>button</code> element doesn't technically require a
    <code>type</code>, but sometimes being explicit is better overall. Buttons
    can be standalone, or they can be used in cluster components for grouping.
  </p>

  <button type="button">Click Me!</button>

  <div class="cmp-cluster">
    <button type="button">No, Click Me!</button>
    <button type="button">No, Me!</button>
    <button type="button">I Want to be Clicked!</button>
  </div>

<pre>
&lt;button type="button"&gt;Click Me!&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;div class="cmp-cluster"&gt;
  &lt;button type="button"&gt;No, Click Me!&lt;/button&gt;
