&lt;/div&gt;
</pre>

  <h2>
    Selects
  </h2>
  <p>
    Before continuing, remember to
    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CUkMCQR4TpY">burn your select tags</a>.
    With that out of the way, if you do decide to use one, here's how it will
    look. Checkboxes or radio buttons are often better choices, though.
  </p>
  <p>
    One thing worth noting is that this requires a wrapper class to make the
    dropdown caret appear. If you forget it, it will look like a regular input.
  </p>

  <div class="elem-select-wrapper">
    <label for="single-select">Single Select</label>
    <select id="single-select" name="single-select">
      <option value="">Choose Something</option>
      <option value="one">Thing One</option>
      <option value="two">Thing Two</option>
      <option value="three">Thing Three</option>
    </select>
  </div>

<pre>
&lt;div class="elem-select-wrapper"&gt;
  &lt;label for="single-select"&gt;Single Select&lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;select id="single-select" name="single-select"&gt;
    &lt;option value=""&gt;Choose Something&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;option value="one"&gt;Thing One&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;option value="two"&gt;Thing Two&lt;/option&gt;
    &lt;option value="three"&gt;Thing Three&lt;/option&gt;
  &lt;/select&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
</pre>

  <h3>
    Multiple Selects
  </h3>
  <p>
    Don't. Just don't. It's a bad idea. But if you do...
  </p>

  <div class="elem-select-wrapper">
    <label for="multiple-select">Multiple Select</label>
    <select id="multiple-select" name="multiple-select" multiple>
      <option value="">Choose Some Things</option>
      <option value="one">Thing One</option>
      <option value="two">Thing Two</option>
      <option value="three">Thing Three</option>
    </select>
  </div>

<pre>
